{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937112401/0771.xml":{"full_text":"Lewis Maps Plans to Guide C. I. O. Thru\nBusiness Recession\nBy RAYMOND CLAPPER\nWith the development of the business recession, the C. I. O.\nenters a new and quite different phase. John L. Lewis, whose\nshrewdness already has been amply demonstrated, is trimming\nsail in order to carry his organization thru the difficult period\nwhich he sees ahead.\nFirst, the spectacular period of initial growth probably is\nss\n4\nover. With members being laid off, it has\nbeen necessary to curtail sharply expendi\nture for organizing effort. Even if it was\nfelt that the earlier rate of expenditure\ncould be maintained, the market is not\nfavorable at the moment to labor or\nganization. Lewis recognized that a busi\nI ness recession would check C. I. O.\u2019s\nprogress.\nThat was one reason why he\nClapper\ndrove so furiously to pile up memberships\nwholesale, without worrying too much\nI about assimilating his recruits into sol\nI idly disciplined organizations. He wanted\nI to get them in while the getting was good.\nAnd events have vindicated his judgment\nthat it was wise to make hay while the\nsun was shining.\nSecond, with many employers suffering severe curtailments\nof earnings, with large lay-offs occurring, Lewis recognizes\nthat the main purpose of C. I. O. now has to shift from a\nfight for higher wages and shorter hours to a struggle to re\nsist wage cuts. Lewis has been in the field too long not to\nrecognize that you can't get wages if the money isn't there in\nthe employer\u2019s till.\nTypical of the position that he may be expected to take is\nhis recommendation to his own anthracite miners.\nHe has\nasked them to vote approval of an extension of their existing\nwage contract. It expires April 30 next. Lewis foresees that\noperators will likely be unable to consider any wage increases.\nThey are having hard going. He is content to try to hold what\nhas already been gained. That, roughly, is the C. I. O. pro\ngram for the immediate future.\nLewis has for a long time been cooling toward the Roosevelt\nAdministration. He is colder than ever now. His complaint is\nthat the Administration, caught off guard by the sudden re\ncession, is without plans for dealing with it except by balancing\nthe budget, which Lewis, in common with a great many others\nhere, regards as impossible. He considers it not only impos\nsible but undesirable, joining in this with a number of econo\nmists who fear that drastic economy now would only speed up\na deflationary spiral. The time for economy was some time\nback. As for balancing the budget when it is certain that re\nduced earnings will result in sharply decreased revenues, every\none here who thinks at all about it knows that the budget\ncan't be balanced until there is recovery.\nLewis has urged upon the Administration the launching of a\ngigantic Government-financed low-cost housing program Ho\nsays England pulled out of the hole with one. When officials\nask where the money is coming from, Lewis points to Social\nSecurity receipts, advocating, as have some economists, that\nthis fund, instead of being allowed to accumulate in a sterile\nreserve, be used with a Government guarantee to finance an\nimmediate extensive low-cost housing development which will\nstimulate heavy industries. That is his chief proposal for Fed\neral action and one which has considerable support outside of\nlabor ranks, and some within the Government.\nAs to the pending wage-and-hour bill, Lewis still supports\nit but not with any steam. He regards it as a crumb which\nlabor will be glad to have. But he expects nothing from it\nbeyond offering protection to northern textile manufacturers\nagainst southern competition. Exempting agricultural, mari\ntime and some other classes of employes, as well as those em\nployed in intrastate activities, and applying only up to a limit\nof 40 cents an hour, the measure would not, in the opinion\nof Lewis, have any material effect generally on labor condi\ntions.\nHis mild interest only increases the doubt that the\nmeasure will be passed at any time soon.\nWhat Lewis is thinking now is important because it re\nveals that the leader of this powerful labor movement is\nkeeping a cool head, is facing the facts and is anxious not to\nrock the boat. That may surprise a good many employers,\nbut it ought to be a welcome surprise.\nIt Seems to Me\nBy Heywood\nBROUN\nW\n'HEN the Duke and Duchess of\nWindsor decided to postpone or\ncancel their visit to America there\nwas much wailing by the merchants\nof New York and other cities.\nIn\ncertain quarters it was felt that the\nexpedition might be a fillip toward\n_ recovery, like re\npeal or an Amer\nican Legion con\nvention\na\nor\n\nfight for the\nheavy weigh t\nchampionshi p.\nAfter all, it had\nbeen announced\nthat the Wind\nsors were bring\ning 60 trunks\u2014\nor was it 70? The\nhairdressers\nof\nBroun\nthe nation im\nplored the Duch\ness to adopt varying styles of coif\nfure in order to relieve unemploy\nment, and tailors felt that the Duke\nmight send every well dressed man\nin to be measured, if only he ap\npeared in public with some slight\ninnovation, such as wearing his din\nner trousers turned up at the bot\ntom. After all, as Prince he all but\nput the starch shirt out of business.\nUnless I am misinformed he ap\npeared at several minor functions\nwearing a sport shirt with his din\nner jacket. When he came to the\nthrone he abandoned this radical\ninnovation, and as far as I know a\nGreenwich Village sculptor and my\n..self were the only ones to carry on\nthe good fight to combine comfort\nand elegance.\nBUT I suspect that the merchants\nmight have been doomed to be\ndisappointed had the Windsors ar\nrived. In the days of his princehood\nthe Duke was known as one of the\nfinest salesmen for the Empire, but\nthere is no record that he main\ntained a balance of trade.\nAt my\nelbow lies a press association story\nof the Duke\u2019s most recent spending\nspree at a church bazaar in Paris.\nThe rector made up for certain An\nglican discourtesies and welcomed\nthe couple warmly. Indeed, he .in\nvited the Duchess to make a speech.\nAnd she did.\nThe rush cable then went on to\nstate, \u201cAfter opening the bazaar the\nDuke and Duchess moved among\nthe guests chatting gaily.\nThey\nspent many francs, doled out by the\nDuke\u2019s equerry, Lieut. Dudley For\nwood. The purchases of the Duchess\nincluded a dish of English marma\nlade, a jar of current jelly, choco\nlate cake, a tin of tea, two boxes of\nbiscuits, three cans of tomato juice,\ntwo pairs of scissors, a penknife,\nChristmas cards, calendars and sev\neral knitted baby jackets to be given\nto the poor.\u201d\nAll right, there can be no quarrel\nwith that. The lady quite obviously\nwas on a spending spree.\nB'\nUT what about the Duke?\nHe\nseems to have kept his head\nabout him during the orgy of ex\ntravagance. The press association\ndispatch notes his purchases in a\nsingle laconic line.\n\u201cThe Duke\nbought a trick cigaret box and a\ntube of tooth paste.\u201d\nUp to this point I was inclined to\nbe amazed by the skill of the cor\nrespondent in reportorial detail But\nfor all that he fluffed his big\nchance.\nA trick cigaret box in\ndeed! As an avid reader of all the\ndoings of the Duke I am curious\nto know\u2014indeed, I demand an an\nswer to the legitimate question\u2014\n\"What was the trick?\u201d\nSIDE GLANCES\nby George Clark\nt\n4\n21\nJI\n3\nbl\n\"I\n\nl\nes\nX2\nsamoreeec.\nSe.\n6\nCoPr p17 MEASERYK\u20ac\nMY*Ra\nws\n\u201cI've been invited to five dances and I brought only four\nevening dresses.\u201d\nPlain Economics\nby John T. Flynn\nNEW YORK\u2014The President has declared that there must\nbe an investigation of rising prices which are having so de\nstructive an effect upon recovery.\nThere ought to be such an investigation. But if it is made,\nit is certain that the one who will be held responsible for\nthese rising prices will be the President himself.\nIn 1933 the President week after\nweek declared that it was his de\nternination to get prices up. Con\ngress took that position also, but\nhe was the leader of the movement.\nOn several occasions he delivered\nto the assembled\nc o r r e spondents\nlectures on the\ndevastating ef\nfect of the low\nof\nlevel\nprice\n1933 and 1934.\nHe went on the\nair and defended\nFlynn\nHe\nhis policy.\nput all his en\nergy behind the\nNRA which had\nthe effect of en\ncouraging trade\nagreements with\nthe direct and indirect objective of\nboosting prices.\nAnd, of course, as soon as the Gov\nernment began pouring its borrowed\nbillions into the market the prices\nbegan to move up.\nNow, of course, the President\nmight take the position that he\nnever intended to have them go\nso high. But this will not hold\nwater. Because he not only intended\nthem to go so high, but much high\ner and he said so publicly many\ntimes. His aim was to force prices\nup to the 1926 level.\nPrices have not yet reached the\n1926 level. If they had things would\nbe very much wore than they are.\nIt was as clear as any future event\ncan be that the moment the Gov\nernment began to create new pur\nchasing power by Federal credit in\nflation, prices would rise. No Presi\ndent or Congress would have to add\nany encouragement to this process.\nThe course of statesmanship would\nhave been to realize that the price\nlevel would move up and that as\nfast as it did it would tend to\ncancel the buying power created by\nthe Government's spending.\nThe Government should have rec\nognized that natural forces would\nforce prices up and that the Gov\nernment, instead of assisting the\nprocess, should have been everlast\ningly on guard to check it and\nslow it up.\nThe President used three stimu\nlants to price rises. First he cre\nated purchasing power by Govern\nment borrowing. Next he devalued\nthe dollar. Next he suspended the\nanti-trust laws to enable trade\ngroups to limit competitive checks\non lowering prices.\nHe is directly responsible for what\nhappened. This is one thing of\nwhich he can truly say that \u201cif it\nhappened that way it is because we\nplanned it that way.\u201d\nit is a little odd, therefore, to\nhave him demand an investigation\nof the causes of high prices.\nCopyright. 1937\n-Diplomacy\u2014More or Less\nRule of Shanghai by Japanese\nCertain, Say Experts Here\nBy JOSEPH H. BAIRD\nFarewell to Shanghai! Farewell to the \u201cParis of the Far\nEast!\u201d Farewell to the island of western culture and Wall-st\nbusiness methods in the once-sleepy Orient!\nThis, of course, isn\u2019t being said officially. A perfunctory\nobjection to Japan\u2019s demand to run Shanghai\u2019s famed inter\nnational settlement will be made by the interested powers.\nThere may be even full-fledged official protests.\nBut the realists in diplomatic and\nmilitary circles, many of whom once\nlived in the western capital by the\nYangtze, foresee the flag of the ris\ning sun floating over the city and\nthe end of its\ne x t raterritorial \u2014\u2014m\nstatus. Japan lias\nshown\nits\nde\nt e r m l nation to L;\ntake over the t*\nbusiness capital\nof China. And\nthe\nStates,\nUnited r\nGreat p\nand\nknow\na\nBritain\nFrance\nthat Japan can\nbe prevented only\nby arms which\nnot\nare\nthey\nBaird\nready to use.\nShanghai. as a city, will remain.\nPhysical damage by bombs and\nshells has been limited mostly to\nthe native quarter.\nBut, under\nJapanese domination, the spirit of\nShanghai, like that of Harbin, will\nchange. Foreign business firms may\nbe forced out as they were in Man\nchuria. Hence the farewells.\nShanghai, built and administered\non Chinese soil by foreigners, was\nperhaps the most international city\nin the world. It combined the gaiety\nof pre-war Paris and the profligacy\nof St. Petersburg with the modern\nbusiness tempo of New York or Lon\ndon.\nIts hundreds of cabarets ranged\nfrom the austere Little Club, where\nambassadors danced with their\nwives, to the sailor-haunted honky\ntonks down by the quais.\nMost popular were the places pat\nterned on New York taxi-dancing\nnight clubs.\nAt one end of the\nroom a Chinese orchestra blared out\nthe latest \u201chot\" tune from Broad\nway. Customers, mostly male, were\nranged along tables on one side,\nwhile across the room were lined the\ndancing girls, largely White Rus\nsians, from whom the men took their\npick.\nDance tickets were 50 cents (Mex),\nor about 12 cents. At the end of the\nweek, each girl turned in her paste\nboards, and the Mura or Nina or\nNatasha who had proved most de\nsirable to the customers received a\nlarge cash prize.\nRace tracks, too, were popular in\nShanghai. The three whippet tracks\ndrew huge crowds each night as did\nthe one horse track in the interna\ntional settlement\nShanghai's International\nClub\nboasted the longest bar in the world,\nand, with Scotch and soda at 12\ncents a drink, it was usually well\nlined.\nThose who liked their drinks in\nmore swanky surroundings went at\ncocktail time to the Country Club\nor the French Club, the American\nClub or one of half a dozen others.\nBut, if Shanghai\u2019s foreign popu\nlation played hard at night, it also\nworked hard during the day as mes\nsengers for western big business in\nthe great Oriental market.\nIn Shanghai are the eastern\nbranches of giant corporations\u2014\nStandard OU, Royal Dutch Shell,\nGeneral Motors, Chase, National\nCity and half a hundred other*,\nbringing western inventions and\nservices to the backward Orient.\nShanghai, as a city, will remain.\nIt probably will continue to be a\ngreat business center. Its night life\nwill not be entirely dimmed. But\nthose who know their Far East be\nlieve that when Japan takes Shang\nhai over, the old city will vanish and\na new and different metropolis will\ntake its place.\nWhat that will be\nlike no one, perhaps not even Tokio,\nknows.\nIndividual Neglected\nWhile We Help the\nMass, He Says\nEditor, The News:\nI\nAM a hard-boiled night watch\nman but your editorial, \"The Doc,\nand Us, on Art,\u201d brought a lump\ninto my throat. God bless you for\nthe words. \u201cA sick child's smile is\nworth a mile of formal corridor.\u201d\nThere is too great a tendency to\nday to help the thousands and pay\nscant attention to the needs of the\nindividual; too great a tendency on\nthe part of managers of charitable\ninstitutions to work for a showing,\nblind to the fact that a little hu\nman sympathy may be the ingre\ndient most needed.\nI get a great kick out of Ernie\nPyle. I followed him on his trip\nthru Alaska\nwith the feeling\nthat I was almost with him. There\nis a fellow who could write an ar\nresting story about an alley cat on\nthe back fence. And Clapper\u2019s ar\nticles from Europe seem not only to\nbe giving us the low-down on con\nditions over there, but a new slant\non some of our own problems. But\nI am most pleased with The News\nbecause when you talk about free\ndom of the press, you really seem\nto mean it.\nFar too many newspapers, when\nthey say \u201cfreedom of the press\"\nmean freedom to sling mud at gov\nernment without even that control\nwhich decency would require. They\nhave no reference to freedom from\ncontrol by advertisers and\nthru\nthem the corporate and monied in\nterests. I could stomach even this\nif such control were confined to\ntheir editorials, but when their sorry\neffort to mold public opinion seeps\ninto their news stories and headlines,\nit is time to make a change. I gave\nup two newspapers for this reason,\notherwise I might never have be\ncome acquainted with The News.\nJOHN MARSHMAN.\nA Rider Takes Issue\nWith Car Company\u2019s\nLatest Placard\nEditor, The News:\nTHE latest street car placard is\nan insult to the sucker's intelli\ngence. It is obviously designed to\nplacate disgruntlement over the ad\nvance in fares.\nThey should stick up a poster\nsomething like this: \u201cWe take all\nthe law allows. If you don\u2019t like it,\nRIDER SEES RED.\nlump it.\"","height":"21096","width":"14488"}}
